    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-05T02:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-05T02:30:00-05:00" n="614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">856E.00/6–546: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Batavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foote</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Batavia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-05T15:00:00+07:30"
                            >June 5, 1946—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 6—10:52 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>240. Sjahrir returned from Djocjakarta and said <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss> leaders agreed Netherlands’ proposals far below expectations.
                    Main objections Netherlands’ failure provide inclusion Sumatra in <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Republic but he said there are many other
                    objections. He said he will draft counter-proposals in few days and forward them
                    to Soekarno at Djocja for his approval. Sjahrir said Dutch never told him that
                    proposals (see my telegram 227, May 27<note n="80" xml:id="d614fn1">See footnote
                        74, <ref target="#pg_821">p. 821</ref>.</note>) were final offers. On
                    previous occasion, however, he said Van Mook told him the offer was final and
                    Van Mook confirmed this to me on two occasions.</p>
                <p>Three <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> ministers have left cabinet and it
                    appears Soekarno, not Sjahrir, will select successors, thus weakening
                    Sjahrir.</p>
                <p>Sjahrir said <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> leaders and cabinet has [<hi
                        rend="italic">have?</hi>] considered possible results of Dutch refusal of
                        <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> counter-proposal but did not indicate
                    that such might be. He added rather subtly that “removal <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Government offices from Batavia to Djocja
                    would depend on circumstances”.</p>
                <p>There is no indication when any meeting between Van Mook and Sjahrir will
                    occur.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Foote</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
